"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Daniel chapters 1–2
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-daniel-1-2-fill.py

Key Christological decisions:
- The stone of 2:34-35 is treated as direct messianic type: Jesus cites it of himself
  (Matt 21:44; Luke 20:17-18); 1 Pet 2:4-8 applies it to Christ.
- 2:45 "stone cut without hands" = Virginal conception; Christ born of no human agency.
- Daniel's Joseph-pattern (elevation from condemned prisoner to first minister) is a type
  of Christ's exaltation from death to God's right hand.
- Ch 1 verses without direct Christ connections receive brief typological entries
  (exile condition, covenant faithfulness in pagan court) rather than strained parallels.
- Nebuchadnezzar's worship of Daniel (2:46) is inadvertent surplus anticipation of the
  universal worship due Christ; Daniel himself does not claim it.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DANIEL = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>The siege of Jerusalem opens the book at the lowest point in Israel\'s covenant history — the beginning of the exile. Jesus enters a world under this same covenant curse: born under Roman occupation, in a land where the Davidic throne had been vacant for six centuries, in the "fullness of time" (<em>pleroma tou chronou</em>, Gal 4:4) when exile conditions still prevailed. The Son of God descends into the exile condition of his people to bear it from within and end it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"The Lord gave Jehoiakim into his power" — the exile is not a defeat of YHWH but his sovereign act. Christ\'s crucifixion follows the same logic: "handed over by the predetermined plan and foreknowledge of God" (Acts 2:23). The temple vessels carried to Babylon anticipate Christ as the true temple (John 2:19-21): what is taken from the earthly house is ultimately returned and surpassed in the one in whom all the fullness of the Godhead dwells bodily (Col 2:9).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Babylonian program of absorbing Israel\'s covenant seed into imperial service — selecting the best of the royal line — anticipates the hostile kingdoms that seek to co-opt, silence, or transform the one who is the true seed. Herod\'s slaughter of the innocents (Matt 2:16-18) is the same impulse: neutralize the covenant child before he can fulfill his mission. Daniel survives through divine protection; Jesus survives through the flight to Egypt and divine timing.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The virtues sought in Daniel and his companions — wisdom (<em>chokmah</em>), knowledge (<em>da\'at</em>), discernment (<em>binah</em>), and beauty — are the covenant gifts that Babylon wants to possess without God. Christ is the one in whom "all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden" (Col 2:3); what the empire cannot manufacture through selection and education, God freely gives in the person of his Son.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The king\'s provision of food and wine — his attempt to nourish the covenant seed on Babylonian resources — is a shadow of every attempt to sustain human life on that which cannot ultimately nourish. Jesus confronts this directly in the wilderness temptation: "man does not live by bread alone" (Matt 4:4, citing Deut 8:3). The true food that sustains covenant life is the word of God, not the king\'s provision.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Daniel and his companions are from the tribe of <strong>Judah</strong> — the royal tribe, the lion\'s tribe (Gen 49:10), the messianic line. Their selection from Judah\'s nobility is not incidental: the story of faithfulness in exile that begins here belongs to the very lineage from which Christ will come. Jesus is "the Lion of the tribe of Judah" (Rev 5:5), the final and definitive member of this covenant line.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The renaming of the four men — Hebrew theophoric names replaced by Babylonian names embedding pagan deities — is the attempt to erase the covenant identity that their names encoded. Jesus receives "the name that is above every name" (Phil 2:9), not through imperial imposition but through divine bestowal at the resurrection; no empire can rename or redefine him. The four men who keep their identity under renamed surfaces anticipate Christ whose identity is indestructible even by crucifixion.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>Daniel\'s resolve not to defile himself</strong> — the covenant faithfulness of the one who refuses contamination in the midst of pagan power. Jesus is the ultimate fulfillment: "holy, innocent, undefiled, separated from sinners" (Heb 7:26), the one who lived the entirety of a human life within pagan imperial conditions without contamination. Daniel\'s resolve models what Christ embodies perfectly: total covenant fidelity within total worldly exposure.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"God granted Daniel favour and compassion in the eyes of the chief official" — the same construction appears of Jesus in Luke 2:52: "Jesus grew in wisdom and stature, and in favour with God and man." The divine favor granted to the faithful servant in exile is the pattern. In Christ it reaches its fullness: the Father\'s voice declares "this is my beloved Son, in whom I am well-pleased" (Matt 3:17) — supreme favor, not earned but established in the covenant relationship between Father and Son.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The official\'s fear of the king — "I am afraid of my lord the king" — illustrates the conflicting loyalties that the world always places before those with earthly authority: fear of human power vs. doing what is right. Jesus confronts this dynamic throughout his ministry; at his trial Pilate fears the crowd more than he fears God (John 19:8, 12-13). Daniel\'s strategy of navigating the official\'s fear with a practical proposal models wisdom-without-compromise.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The steward who manages the practical arrangement — the mediating figure between the official\'s fear and the young men\'s need — is a minor image of those who serve as intermediaries making possible the faithful person\'s survival within empire. The church\'s existence within hostile social structures often depends on such mediating relationships. Christ himself used the existing social and religious structures of his day even while transcending them.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The ten-day test on vegetables and water — a vulnerable proposal, entirely trusting to God\'s provision within the constraint of faithfulness. The willingness to be tested, to submit the outcome to God\'s demonstration, models the faith of the righteous throughout Scripture. Jesus submits to the forty-day wilderness test (Matt 4:1-11) in which his covenant faithfulness is tested to the limit; he passes where Israel failed.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The appeal to visible comparison — "see our appearance" — assumes that covenant faithfulness will be visibly vindicated. The Sermon on the Mount makes the same claim: the kingdom-shaped life will be visibly different, "your light will shine before men" (Matt 5:16). The evidence of God\'s blessing is not always what the world expects, but it is genuinely evident.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The steward agrees and tests them — a small act of trust granting a small amount of freedom to be faithful. The incremental nature of faithfulness in exile: not dramatic confrontation at every point, but negotiating space for covenant integrity within the constraints of imperial service. Jesus operates within the structures of Second Temple Judaism and Roman occupation, seeking the possible rather than demanding the impossible.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The visible result of faithfulness: "they looked healthier and better nourished than all the young men eating the king\'s food." The counterintuitive outcome — those on lesser provisions are visibly superior — is the logic of the kingdom throughout: the last are first, the weak are strong, the one who loses his life saves it (Mark 8:35). The cross and resurrection is the ultimate form of this pattern: the one who seems defeated is raised to indestructible life.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The steward quietly removes their royal food and replaces it with vegetables — the system accommodates covenant faithfulness without confrontation, not because systems always do this, but because God works within them. The quietly faithful life is often protected in ways unseen. Not every act of covenant fidelity requires martyrdom; much of it is sustained by small providential arrangements.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>God gave wisdom and understanding to the four men; to Daniel also understanding of visions and dreams</strong> — divine wisdom and prophetic gift, both given by God. Christ is himself the Wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:24) and the one in whom "all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden" (Col 2:3). What God gives to Daniel as gift, Christ is as Person: the source and ground of all wisdom, not merely its recipient. Jesus astonished the temple teachers at age twelve (Luke 2:47) — the same pattern: wisdom beyond the academy, given by God.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The appointed time arrives — the period of training concludes and Daniel stands before the king. All of God\'s providential preparation in Daniel\'s life converged on this moment of royal presentation. In the same way, Jesus appears at the "fullness of time" (Gal 4:4) — after centuries of preparation — to stand before the judgment seat of the world and the throne of God as the qualified, prepared, anointed servant.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"None was found equal to them" — a superlative that the text underlines. The four stand above all others in the empire\'s wisdom establishment. This anticipates the NT description of Christ: "one greater than Solomon is here" (Matt 12:42); "one greater than Jonah is here" (Matt 12:41); "no man ever spoke the way this man speaks" (John 7:46). Daniel\'s incomparable position among the wise of Babylon is a shadow of Christ\'s absolute supremacy.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Ten times superior to all the magicians and enchanters — the wisdom of God, given through covenant faithfulness, surpasses the best human wisdom-systems can produce. Jesus\'s teaching "astonished" even his opponents (Matt 22:22, 33, 46); in every engagement with the religious establishment, the scribes and Pharisees and Sadducees are silenced. Not ten times but infinitely superior: "in him are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3).</p>',
    "21": '<p>Daniel remained until the first year of King Cyrus — he outlasted the entire Babylonian empire and lived to see the beginning of the restoration. This longevity-in-faithfulness models the One who "is the same yesterday, today, and forever" (Heb 13:8) — who outlasts every empire, who is "before all things" and in whom "all things hold together" (Col 1:17). Daniel\'s career spans one empire; Christ\'s reign spans all of them.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>Nebuchadnezzar\'s disturbing dream — the king of the world empire cannot sleep, cannot find peace, cannot understand the meaning of what God is showing him. The one who rules the visible world is anxious, and the wisdom his own system provides is helpless. Christ comes into a world in exactly this condition: the powerful are restless, the wise are baffled, and only the revelation of God through his Son can answer the question of what history means and where it is going (Matt 11:25-27).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The four categories of Babylonian wise men — all called, all helpless. The fullest human wisdom cannot access the divine council. Jesus identifies this same limitation when he says "no one knows the Father except the Son and those to whom the Son chooses to reveal him" (Matt 11:27). The empire\'s consultation of its best minds produces nothing; the revelation comes through the covenant servant.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The king\'s "spirit was troubled" (<em>ruach</em> disturbed) — the same language as Gen 1:2 (the Spirit moving) and Ps 77:3 (the troubled soul seeking God). The empire\'s unrest is the condition into which Christ comes to bring peace: "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you" (John 14:27).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The language shift to Aramaic at this point — the international language — signals that what follows concerns the nations, not just Israel. The "God of heaven" revealed through Daniel\'s intervention addresses the whole world\'s empires. Christ\'s great commission is equally international: "all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore and make disciples of all nations" (Matt 28:18-19) — the authority that Daniel demonstrates over Babylon\'s kingdom is claimed universally by Christ.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The king\'s impossible demand — tell the dream AND the interpretation — is the demand that only God can meet. The empire demands of its wisdom class what only divine revelation can provide. Jesus enters the human situation precisely as the one who can fulfill the impossible: to reveal God, to atone for sin, to defeat death — demands that no merely human figure can meet.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The promise of gifts and honor for the one who answers — the world system rewards what it can use. But what the world needs most (true revelation of God and of what is to come) cannot be purchased or rewarded into existence; it must be given as a free gift of grace. Jesus gives freely: "come to me, all who are weary and heavy-laden, and I will give you rest" (Matt 11:28).</p>',
    "7": '<p>The wise men\'s second appeal for the king to provide the dream — exposing that their system is merely interpretive, not revelatory. They can work with given data but cannot access what is hidden. This is the fundamental limitation of unaided human wisdom in every age; it explains why the incarnation was necessary — only one who is himself the Truth (John 14:6) can reveal the Father.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The king sees through the delay — he knows they are stalling. The wisdom establishments of every age eventually face the exposure that they cannot deliver what they promise. The Pharisees and scribes are likewise exposed by Jesus: they "shut the kingdom of heaven in people\'s faces" (Matt 23:13) and "bind heavy burdens" without giving the key of knowledge (Luke 11:52).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The king accuses the wise men of lying — and he is right. Systems of human wisdom that claim to mediate the divine while having no genuine access to it are inherently deceptive. Jesus\'s repeated indictment of religious hypocrisy follows the same logic: claiming to represent God while blocking access to God is the fundamental corruption of the covenant tradition.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"No man on earth can reveal this" — the honest confession that precedes revelation. This admission of human incapacity is the theological precondition for receiving divine revelation: "blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven" (Matt 5:3). The wise men\'s confession of incapacity, involuntary as it is, points to the epistemological need that only Christ fills.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"The gods do not dwell with flesh" — the pagan theologians articulate the doctrine of divine transcendence in its negative form: the divine and human realms are separated by an unbridgeable gap. The incarnation is God\'s definitive answer to this statement: "the Word became flesh and dwelt among us" (John 1:14, using <em>eskēnōsen</em>, "pitched his tent"). The gods do not dwell with flesh; but the one true God does.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The decree to destroy all the wise men — a death sentence that would include Daniel and his companions. They face death through no fault of their own, caught in the crisis created by others. This mirrors the situation of Jesus, condemned under false pretenses, bearing a sentence he did not deserve. The innocent is threatened by the unjust exercise of imperial power.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Daniel and his companions "sought" (from the same root as prayer) — they are sought for execution. The one who will provide the solution is himself under threat of death. Jesus is condemned and crucified before his exaltation; death is the path through which the revelation of God\'s power comes. Daniel\'s life is at risk when the answer to Babylon\'s crisis is given.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Daniel responds to the crisis with discretion and wisdom — "prudence and wisdom" (<em>ta\'am u-vevet</em>). He does not panic, does not demand special treatment, but works calmly within the system to create space for God to act. The wisdom of God operates with <em>sōphrosynē</em> (sober-mindedness) not hysteria; Jesus consistently demonstrates this: unhurried, purposeful, never reactive but always responsive.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Daniel asks for the time to explain what is happening — gathering information before acting. Wisdom begins with understanding the situation. Jesus likewise takes time to understand interlocutors\' actual questions before answering, often turning questions back to expose what is really being asked (Matt 22:15-22; John 3:10).</p>',
    "16": '<p>Daniel goes to the king to request time — a direct appeal to the very power threatening his life. Jesus too engages directly with the authorities that threaten him: before Pilate, before the high priest, he does not evade but answers plainly. The approach to the throne of power is not avoided but transformed into an opportunity for the truth to be spoken.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Daniel goes to his companions — the crisis is brought to the community of the faithful for intercession. Jesus likewise, on the night he is betrayed, goes to the garden with his disciples to pray (Matt 26:36-46), though they sleep while he prays. The covenant community gathered in prayer at the moment of crisis is the pattern; Christ perfects it as the one who prays with perfect persistence.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Plead for mercy from the God of heaven about this mystery" — <em>rachamim</em> (mercy) sought from the God who alone can reveal the hidden things. Christ is the "one mediator between God and man" (1 Tim 2:5) who intercedes for us; he "always lives to make intercession" (Heb 7:25). The prayer Daniel organizes is a shadow of the intercession Christ continually makes at the Father\'s right hand.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>The mystery was revealed to Daniel in a night vision</strong> — the hidden thing disclosed through divine gift. This is the NT definition of the gospel itself: "the revelation of the mystery hidden for long ages but now disclosed and through the prophetic writings made known to all nations" (Rom 16:25-26); "the mystery of Christ... in other generations not made known to the sons of men" now revealed (Eph 3:4-5). Daniel\'s night vision of what the empires cannot see is the first great disclosure of the shape of the Messiah\'s kingdom.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Daniel\'s blessing of God — praising him for wisdom, power, and the changing of times and kings. This is the posture of the one who has received revelation: immediate worship, not pride in the knowledge received. Jesus likewise praises the Father immediately after receiving his mission: "I thank you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, that you have hidden these things from the wise and understanding and revealed them to little children" (Matt 11:25).</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>"He removes kings and establishes kings; he gives wisdom to the wise"</strong> — the sovereignty of God over all earthly power. Paul draws on exactly this claim: "there is no authority except from God, and those that exist have been instituted by God" (Rom 13:1). Christ is the one through whom all this sovereign rule operates: "all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me" (Matt 28:18); Col 1:16-17, "all things were created through him and for him... and in him all things hold together."</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>"He uncovers deep and hidden things; light itself resides with him"</strong> — the theological claim that Daniel makes of the God of heaven is what John says of the incarnate Son: "in him was life, and the life was the light of men. The light shines in the darkness" (John 1:4-5). The divine attribute of being the source of light and the revealer of hidden things is concentrated in the person of Christ, who is "the light of the world" (John 8:12; 9:5).</p>',
    "23": '<p>Daniel\'s personal thanksgiving — "to you, O God of my fathers, I give thanks and praise." The address "God of my fathers" is the covenant formula; Daniel stands in the line of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, whose God he worships. Jesus is the fulfillment of that covenant line (Matt 1:1, "son of Abraham, son of David") and addresses God in the same intimacy — "Abba, Father" (Mark 14:36) — making the covenant personal.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Daniel goes to save the wise men — he intercedes for those who would have been executed. This is the Christ-pattern: the innocent one who has received wisdom and revelation uses it not for personal advancement but to save those who were under a death sentence. "For the Son of Man came to seek and save the lost" (Luke 19:10). Daniel spares the Babylonian wise men; Christ spares humanity.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Arioch brings Daniel hurriedly to the king as "a man who can tell you the interpretation" — the one who can answer what no one else can. Jesus is introduced with similar superlatives: "Rabbi, we know that you are a teacher come from God, for no one can do these signs that you do unless God is with him" (John 3:2). The recognition that this person has unique access to divine truth precedes formal acknowledgment of who he is.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The king asks Daniel directly: "Can you do this?" — the challenge question that the whole wisdom system had failed. Jesus is asked parallel challenge questions: "Who gave you this authority?" (Matt 21:23); "Are you the Christ?" (Luke 22:67). In both cases, the answer comes not by self-assertion but through the demonstration of what God has given.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Daniel immediately disclaims his own ability — "no wise man, enchanter, magician, or diviner can explain this mystery to the king." Jesus similarly redirects attention from himself to the Father: "the Son can do nothing of his own accord, but only what he sees the Father doing" (John 5:19); "my teaching is not mine, but his who sent me" (John 7:16). Both the prophet and the Son attribute the revelation entirely to the God who sends them.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>"There is a God in heaven who reveals mysteries"</strong> — Daniel\'s great confession becomes Paul\'s definition of the gospel: "the mystery hidden for ages and generations but now revealed to his saints... which is Christ in you, the hope of glory" (Col 1:26-27). The God who revealed what would happen "in the last days" to Nebuchadnezzar has now disclosed that mystery fully in the person of Jesus Christ. Daniel glimpsed the shape; the NT announces the name.</p>',
    "29": '<p>God answered the king\'s own pondering — meeting Nebuchadnezzar where he was, with what he was already wondering about. Jesus consistently meets people in their actual questions: the woman at the well and her thirst (John 4:7-26), Nicodemus and his theological puzzles (John 3:1-15), the rich young ruler and his question about eternal life (Matt 19:16-22). Divine revelation is responsive, not generic.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Daniel\'s explicit disclaimer of personal superior wisdom — "not because of any wisdom that is in me more than all living." Jesus takes the same posture: "I do nothing on my own authority, but speak just as the Father taught me" (John 8:28). The true mediator of divine revelation presents himself as transparent to the God who sends him, not as the independent source.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The great statue — gold head, silver chest, bronze belly, iron legs, clay-and-iron feet — is the image of human imperial glory, the <em>tsalma</em> that echoes Gen 1:26 (<em>tselem</em>). Where humanity is called to be the image of God, the empires create their own image of human power. Jesus is "the image of the invisible God" (Col 1:15), "the exact imprint of God\'s nature" (Heb 1:3) — the true and living image, replacing every counterfeit with the genuine.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The statue\'s descending value from gold to iron with clay — the kingdoms of this world decline in covenantal authority even as their political force increases. The NT sees this pattern consummated in the beast of Revelation whose great power is matched by deep corruption. Christ introduces a kingdom of an entirely different order — not a higher-grade metal in the same sequence, but a material from outside the sequence altogether: the stone.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The iron-clay mixture — strength without coherence, force without unity. The divided kingdom that cannot hold together despite apparent might. Paul\'s diagnosis of humanity without Christ is similar: strong in self-will but fragmented, each pursuing their own interests, held together by nothing lasting (Eph 2:14 — "dividing wall of hostility"; Gal 5:15 — "if you bite and devour one another"). Christ is the one who makes the two one (Eph 2:14-16).</p>',
    "34": '<p><strong>The stone cut without hands that destroys the statue</strong> — Jesus explicitly identifies himself as this stone. Luke 20:17-18: "the stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone... Everyone who falls on that stone will be broken to pieces, and when it falls on anyone, it will crush him." Matt 21:44 applies the same text. 1 Pet 2:4-8 builds the whole doctrine of the church on this stone: "a living stone rejected by men but in the sight of God chosen and precious." The stone struck at the weakest point (the feet) — Christ confronted the fundamental fragility of human empire, not its strongest point.</p>',
    "35": '<p><strong>The stone became a great mountain filling the whole earth</strong> — the kingdom of God beginning small (the mustard seed of Matt 13:31-32) and filling the whole earth. The chaff blown away on the threshing floor = the judgment metaphor of John the Baptist (Matt 3:12). Jesus is the stone that becomes the mountain; his kingdom, inaugurated at his first coming and consummated at his second, will fill the earth as the waters cover the sea (Hab 2:14). The permanent, indestructible nature of his kingdom contrasts with every empire that has ever risen and fallen.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Daniel\'s announcement: "this is the dream; now we will give the interpretation" — the transition from revelation to explanation is exactly what the entire NT does with the OT. The dream of Daniel 2 was given; the interpretation now provided is: the stone is Christ; the mountain is his kingdom. The NT is the interpretation of the OT dream.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Nebuchadnezzar is the king of kings — but only because the God of heaven gave it. Jesus is <em>ho basileus tōn basileōn</em>, the King of kings (Rev 17:14; 19:16), not because a God above him gave it but because he himself is the God who gave all earthly dominion its authority. The title Nebuchadnezzar receives by divine grant, Jesus holds by divine nature.</p>',
    "38": '<p>The dominion over beasts and birds — the Adamic mandate (Gen 1:28) restored to the head of the first kingdom. Christ is the last Adam (1 Cor 15:45-47) who recapitulates and surpasses Adam\'s original dominion; in him the creation mandate is fulfilled and the curse of Gen 3 is reversed. The head of gold anticipates the Head of the new humanity.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The inferior and then bronze kingdoms that follow — history moves through these empires toward the moment the stone strikes. Each empire is necessary in the sequence; none is the answer. The Medo-Persian kingdom enabled the Jewish return from exile; the Greek kingdom spread the language in which the NT was written; the Roman empire provided the roads and political framework for the gospel\'s first expansion — all unknowingly serving the coming kingdom.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The fourth kingdom — strong as iron, breaking everything. Rome\'s military and administrative power was real and historically unprecedented. But the kingdom inaugurated in the Roman period (Christ\'s birth "in the days of Caesar Augustus," Luke 2:1) is of a completely different order. The iron empire that crucified Jesus was simultaneously the instrument through which the stone was cut from the mountain.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The divided kingdom — partly strong, partly brittle. The political fragmentation following Rome\'s decline maps onto the subsequent history of European and Near Eastern powers, but more importantly the verse emphasizes that every human kingdom carries within it the seed of its own division. Christ alone builds a kingdom that is not divided against itself (Mark 3:24-25), because he himself is the foundation and the bond of unity (Eph 4:3-6).</p>',
    "42": '<p>The toes — partly iron, partly clay — signal the persistence of this brittle mixture to the end of the statue. All of human history\'s political arrangements share this fundamental instability: strength mixed with fragility, force mixed with incoherence. The stone does not strike at the height of the statue\'s glory but at its foundational weakness — as the cross struck at the apparent hour of the empire\'s greatest power over Jesus.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"They will mingle but will not hold together" — the failure of human social bonding through politics, marriage alliances, or shared interest. Only covenant can create lasting unity — the covenant that Christ establishes in his blood (Luke 22:20) creates "one new humanity" (Eph 2:15) out of those who had no natural bond. Where iron and clay cannot adhere, Christ\'s love "binds everything together in perfect harmony" (Col 3:14).</p>',
    "44": '<p><strong>"The God of heaven will set up a kingdom that will never be destroyed"</strong> — the direct announcement of the messianic kingdom. Luke 1:32-33 echoes this directly: "the Lord God will give him the throne of his father David, and he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end." Heb 12:28: "we are receiving a kingdom that cannot be shaken." The kingdom Christ inaugurates is the eternal kingdom of Dan 2:44 — its establishment begins with the incarnation, its fullness comes at the consummation.</p>',
    "45": '<p><strong>The stone cut from the mountain without human hands</strong> — the Virgin Birth: Christ born "not of blood, nor of the will of the flesh, nor of the will of man, but of God" (John 1:13); "conceived of the Holy Spirit" (Matt 1:18-20); "the holy thing to be born will be called the Son of God" (Luke 1:35). No human agency produces him; he is cut from the mountain of God\'s own being, entering human history without the ordinary mechanism of human generation. The dream is "certain" and "the interpretation trustworthy" (<em>aman</em>, sure/firm) — as certain as the resurrection.</p>',
    "46": '<p><strong>Nebuchadnezzar fell on his face and paid homage to Daniel</strong> — the king of the greatest empire on earth prostrates before the Jewish exile who brought him the word of God. The gesture is misdirected (Daniel is not divine), but it anticipates the moment when "every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord" (Phil 2:10-11). What Nebuchadnezzar gives to Daniel in confused gratitude, the whole creation will one day give rightly to Christ.</p>',
    "47": '<p>"Your God is the God of gods and Lord of kings, and a revealer of mysteries" — Nebuchadnezzar\'s confession is formally correct. The NT amplifies each title: "God of gods" → Christ is "the name above every name" (Phil 2:9); "Lord of kings" → "King of kings and Lord of lords" (Rev 19:16); "revealer of mysteries" → Christ in whom "are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3), the one through whom the mystery hidden for ages is now revealed (Rom 16:25-26).</p>',
    "48": '<p>Daniel elevated to chief ruler over the entire province of Babylon and head of all the wise men — the Joseph-pattern complete: from threatened prisoner to first minister through divine wisdom and divine timing. Jesus is exalted from the condemned cross to God\'s right hand (Acts 2:33; Phil 2:9-11), appointed "heir of all things" (Heb 1:2), given "all authority in heaven and on earth" (Matt 28:18). The exile\'s exaltation is the Messiah\'s pattern.</p>',
    "49": '<p>Daniel\'s first act of power is intercession for his companions — using his newly granted authority to elevate Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. Christ\'s first act at God\'s right hand is intercession for his people: "he always lives to make intercession for them" (Heb 7:25); "who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us" (Rom 8:34). Power given by God is immediately and characteristically deployed in the service of others.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'daniel')
    merge_comm(existing, DANIEL)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'daniel', existing)
    print('Daniel 1-2 mkt-christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
